      "content": "My apologies for the goblin distraction. Let's focus on the mushy spots and root rot. If you notice the mushy spots on the leaves, it's a sign that the plant's roots are not getting enough oxygen. This can happen when the soil stays too wet for too long. Root rot is like a goblin's lair that's been flooded—it's a no-go zone for healthy roots. To tell if it's root rot versus something else, check the roots themselves. Healthy roots are firm and white or tan. If they're brown, mushy, and smell bad, that's a clear sign of root rot. To prevent this, make sure your Monstera's pot has drainage holes, and don't let the soil stay soggy. Water it when the top inch of soil feels dry to the touch. If you're still unsure, you might want to remove the plant from its pot and check the roots directly. If they're healthy, you can replant it in fresh, well-draining soil. Remember, a plant's health is like a goblin's treasure—it's worth the effort to keep it safe and sound.",
